This paper is about Named Entity Recognition (NER) in natural language processing, which is a subfield of computational linguistics and falls under the Computer Science category. Specifically, the paper proposes a semi-supervised annotation framework and a neural correction model to improve the quality and coverage of NER datasets. This work involves machine learning and deep learning techniques, which are commonly studied in sub-categories such as cs.CL (Computation and Language) and cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence). The use of BERT, a popular pre-trained language model, also suggests a focus on natural language processing and machine learning. Additionally, the paper evaluates the proposed model on six NER datasets, which may relate to sub-categories such as cs.LG (Machine Learning), cs.IR (Information Retrieval), and cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing). Overall, cs.CL and cs.AI are the most likely sub-categories, followed by cs.LG, cs.IR, and cs.NE.
